com.ti.debug.engine.scripting

Class DebugSession

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.ti.ccstudio.scripting.ScriptSession
      • com.ti.debug.engine.scripting.DebugSession
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    ScriptingTimeout, IScriptSession, com.ti.debug.engine.IGenericComponent

    public class DebugSession
extends com.ti.ccstudio.scripting.ScriptSession
implements com.ti.debug.engine.IGenericComponent, ScriptingTimeout
    This class encapsulates all of the debugging operations for a given target. A DebugSession object is created by calling DebugServer.openSession().

    You may create as many Debug Sessions as needed to support multi-processor debugging. Each instance of this class maintains reference to the parent ScriptingEnvironment object, therefore, each Debug Session will share the same timeout, log file, and error reporting.

    ScriptingEnvironment env = new ScriptingEnvironment();

    DebugServer myDebugServer = (DebugServer) env.getServer("DebugServer.1");
    DebugSession myDebugSession = myDebugServer.openSession("*", "*");

    ...

    myDebugSession.terminate();
    myDebugServer.stop();

      • getConfig

        public java.lang.String getConfig()
        Returns the full path to the target configuration file that was used to generate this DebugSession object. This string should corresponding with the string passed into the last call to DebugServer.setConfig(<string>) before opening the session. If no call was made to DebugServer.setConfig(<string>), this function will return the default CCS target configuration, based on the environment variable DEFAULT_CCS_TARGET_CONFIGURATION. If the DebugSession is created for a thread or an event history task, this should return the null String
        Returns:
        String full path to target configuration

      • getScriptTimeout

        public int getScriptTimeout()
        Get the timeout value (which specifies the amount of time to wait for underlying calls to the DebugServer to return) of this session. Call setScriptTimeout to change the timeout value.

        The default value will be the timeout value of the environment.
        Specified by:
        getScriptTimeout in interface ScriptingTimeout
        Returns:
        Time in milliseconds to wait for scripting calls. This will be the environment value if setScriptTimeout has not been called on this session; otherwise, it will return the session timeout value. If the timeout value is infinite, then -1 will be returned.
        See Also:
        setScriptTimeout(int)

      • resetScriptTimeout

        public void resetScriptTimeout()
        Resets the timeout value (which specifies the amount of time to wait for underlying calls to the DebugServer to return) for the session. This will make the session use the environment timeout value until setScriptTimeout is called again on this session.

      • setScriptTimeout

        public void setScriptTimeout(int nTimeout)
        Sets the timeout value (which specifies the amount of time to wait for underlying calls to the DebugServer to return) for the session. The default value will be the timeout value of the environment.
        Parameters:
        nTimeout - time in milliseconds. This value will override the environment timeout values for methods associated with the session. Pass a negative number in this parameter to set the timeout to infinite.
        See Also:
        getScriptTimeout()

      • terminate

        public void terminate()
               throws ScriptingException
        Close this DebugSession. Unload and dispose all child objects created by this session. If you try to access any of the child objects (breakpoint, symbol, memory, etc.) after the session has been terminated a NullPointerException will be thrown by that call.
